        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>1816 DeLancey Place&#44;<lb/>
                Philadelphia.<lb/>
                Jan. 19<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 83.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Mr Morais.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am sure you<lb/> will excuse my delay in<lb/> acknowledging your kind<lb/> note and the article I wish<lb/>ed to see&#44; when you hear<lb/> of the serious illness of<lb/> my dear Father&#44; which<lb/> has occupied all our time<lb/> and thoughts.  He was<lb/> taken with a chill last<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Friday which was the be&#45;<lb/>ginning of an attack<lb/> of erysipelas in the face.<lb/>  He was very ill for sever&#45;<lb/>al days&#44; but is decided&#45;<lb/>ly better to&#45;day and we<lb/> hope will continue to<lb/> improve.<lb/></p>
            <p>I think your criti&#45;<lb/>cism of Mrs Magures&#39;<lb/> book perfectly fair and<lb/> just&#44; and your notes<lb/> will make my copy<lb/> more valuable to me.<lb/>  Of course I have not been<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>able to read your an&#45;<lb/>swer to Dr Smith&#44; but am<lb/> looking forward to it.<lb/>  Will you please say to<lb/> Miss Nina that my ab&#45;<lb/>sence from Sunday<lb/> School is caused by<lb/> more pressing claims<lb/> and not by want of<lb/> interest.  I hope she is<lb/> comfortable in her new<lb/> quarters.<lb/></p>
            <p>You may be sure<lb/> though you will not see<lb/> us in Synagogue&#44; that<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>our hearts are full of<lb/> gratitude to our Heaven<lb/>ly Father for sparing<lb/> us our earthly one.<lb/></p>
            <p>With kind regards<lb/> I am very truly yours<lb/>
                Laura Mordecai<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
